LayoutNode.Content: This year's senior class at Kent State University wasn't even born when Michael Keaton famously uttered two words as the Caped Crusader onthe big screen.
LayoutNode.SRC: This year's senior class at Kent State University wasn't even born when Michael Keaton famously uttered two words as the Caped Crusader on the big screen.

LayoutNode.Content: However, the new generation hasn't forgotten about the original cinematic Dark Knight, as Keaton showed when he brought the house down withthe final two words of his commencement speech on Wednesday.
LayoutNode.SRC: However, the new generation hasn't forgotten about the original cinematic Dark Knight, as Keaton showed when he brought the house down withthe final two words of his commencement speech on Wednesday.

LayoutNode.Content: Michael Keaton closed his commencement speech at Kent State with "I'mBatman." And this is why Michael Keaton is the best. pic.twitter.com/20H1B99aCl — TODD SPENCE (@Todd_Spence) May 16, 2018
LayoutNode.SRC:
Michael Keaton closed his commencement speech at Kent State with "I'm Batman."

And this is why Michael Keaton is the best. pic.twitter.com/20H1B99aCl— TODD SPENCE (@Todd_Spence) May 16, 2018

LayoutNode.Content: "I've got two words that I want you all to remember,'' he said. "They're very important, and if I leave you with anything, I'm going to leave you withthese two words. And those two words are: 'I'm Batman.'''
LayoutNode.SRC: "I've got two words that I want you all to remember,'' he said. "They're very important, and if I leave you with anything, I'm going to leave you with these two words. And those two words are: 'I'm Batman.'''

LayoutNode.Content: Keaton, 66, played the starring role in Tim Burton's "Batman" in 1989 and again in "Batman Returns" in 1992.
LayoutNode.SRC: Keaton, 66, played the starring role in Tim Burton's "Batman" in 1989 and again in "Batman Returns" in 1992.

LayoutNode.Content: The Oscar-nominated star of "Beetlejuice, "Birdman" and "Spotlight" said on TODAY in 2015 that he was "up for anything" and would return to playing Batman if given the chance.
LayoutNode.SRC: The Oscar-nominated star of "Beetlejuice, "Birdman" and "Spotlight" said on TODAY in 2015 that he was "up for anything" and would return toplaying Batman if given the chance.

LayoutNode.Content: "When I did 'Batman,' really it was more a matter of ... we were figuring out a lot as we went along," he said. "The character was really ... BruceWayne. That was my way in. ... The rest of the stuff was really just trying to figure out how to manage to do any type of acting inside a giant blackrubber suit."
LayoutNode.SRC: "When I did 'Batman,' really it was more a matter of ... we were figuring out a lot as we went along," he said. "The character was really ... Bruce Wayne. That was my way in. ... The rest of the stuff was really just trying to figure out how to manage to do any type of acting inside a giant black rubber suit."

LayoutNode.Content: Now all we need is Jack Nicholson asking a group of college graduates if they've ever danced with the devil in the pale moonlight andcommencement speaking season will be complete.
